[4.25]
<TEXT>sadeśānena vidyeśair{ }nava pañca pavitrakaiḥ |
<TEXT>sādhyamantroparaktāṃgair{ }anvitān{ }abhimantritān ||</TEXT>%

<NOTE>There is a note in the lower marginal which reads: <foreign>1 tatra sāṃgasādhyamantramūlamantraśaktiś cātra pūjyaḥ</foreign>.</NOTE>

<TR>They should have been recited over using [either] the nine [mantras of] Sadāśiva (<foreign>sadeśānena</foreign>) and the Vidyeśas, [or] using the five brahmamantras (<foreign>pavitrakaiḥ</foreign>), coloured in form [when visualised] in accordance with [whatever is] the [chosen] mantra that is to be propitiated.
</TR>
<NOTE>We have assumed the literal sense of \skt{uparakta}, supposing that the colour of these mantra-deities is harmonised with the colour of the sādhyamantra, but it is possible that the mantras themselves are in some way “coloured”, in other words inflected to accord with the sādhyamantra.
As for the optionality regarding the use of the nine mantras (Sadāśiva and the 8 Vidyeśas) or the five brahmamantras, this is made explicit in the modified version of this verse given in the Uttara-Kāmika. </NOTE>

Note that in the modified account of ācāryābhiṣeka in Uttara-Kāmika 24 there is no reference to the inflection of the colours in accordance with the sādhyamantra, which suggests deliberate modification to reduce the importance of siddhi-seeking:
navadhaa pa~ncadhaa vaapi sarvadhaanyoparisthitaan |
gha.taan vaa kala"saan vaatha sakuurcaan saapidhaanakam || 34 ||
sa suutraan sodakaan gandharatnasvar.navaraanvitaan |
